commentPostTextItems.html: India have won the match by 23 runs (D/L revised target)
For a complete discussion related to who has reached the final to play Australia, visit CricInfo's footnotes section
Presentations
Winner receiving USD 1500. loser getting USD 750
Man of the match will receive USD 500
Man of the match adjudicator talks about Tendulkar and Ganguly batting well
And for Sri Lanka, Jayasuriya blazing away, Atapattu supporting him and Jayawardene did very well
But, lo and behold
You will not guess who the man of the match is
It is Robin Singh!
For his most economical bowling
Robin Singh picks up USD 500
Losing team's captain Sanath Jayasuriya....
Jayasuriya talks about the confusion when he was told about 40 overs, and then later 42 overs
Picks up the cheque for USD 750
Tendulkar now

Tendulkar feels very sad about in spite of playing extremely well today they had to miss the final because of poor display earlier and assures that he will be going to Singapore for the Coca-Cola Challenge between India, West Indies and Zimbabwe
Picks up USD 1500
That is it folks. There will be the final to follow, between Australia and Sri Lanka
The final will be a day/nighter
Good bye from all of us, and do follow the NatWest Trophy Final going on right now in CricInfo

Rain interrupted play at 2:45pm to 3:35pm with Sri Lanka on 22/0 after 5 overs. According to clause 11.2 in the One Day International Playing Conditions this should have prevented India from qualifying for the final ("Only those matches where results were achieved and where the Duckworth/Lewis method for recalculating the target score was not utilised will count for the purpose of net run rate calculations."). However, all available evidence indicates that this rule had been ignored/forgotten and Sri Lanka needed to score 222 runs off 40 overs to qualify for the final.

Further to the above comic farce, at 4:18pm (SL 71/0 off 12 overs) the match referee interrupted the match to inform the umpires that a miscalculation was made and that it should be a 42 over match. The Sri Lankan target to win was 're-revised' to 271 in 42 overs and the apparent target (pending clarification on why the ICC playing conditions were not followed) to qualify for the final calculated to be 232. No further adjustment was made to the fielding restrictions.
